\section{Alignment model}{

tlframe separates alignment into two orthogonal axes, following the
same model as RTF and LaTeX/tabularray:\tabular{llll}{
   Parameter \tab Axis \tab Controls \tab Values \cr
   \code{align} \tab Horizontal \tab Left-to-right text positioning \tab \code{"left"}, \code{"center"}, \code{"right"}, \code{"decimal"} \cr
   \code{valign} \tab Vertical \tab Top-to-bottom content positioning \tab \code{"top"}, \code{"middle"}, \code{"bottom"} \cr
}


\strong{\code{align}} (horizontal) is a \strong{paragraph-level} property — it controls how
each line of text is positioned within the cell width. Most cells need this.

\strong{\code{valign}} (vertical) is a \strong{cell-level} property — it controls where the
content block sits when the cell is taller than needed. This matters only
when rows have unequal content height (e.g., a single-line label next to a
multi-line label). For single-line body rows, \code{valign} has no visible
effect.

They combine freely: a cell can be \verb{align = "right", valign = "bottom"}
(text right-aligned, sitting at the bottom of a tall row).
